@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Privacy Policy";
}

<div class="py-4">
    <h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>
    <p class="text-muted">Last updated: whenever we last remembered this page existed.</p>

    <p>
        Welcome to the Board Game League privacy policy, a document that exists primarily so that
        this sentence can exist. By using this site, rolling a die on it, or simply glancing at it
        from across the room, you agree to the terms below, which were drafted with the same rigor
        typically applied to house rules in Monopoly.
    </p>

    <h4>1. What we collect</h4>
    <p>
        We collect the bare minimum required to keep track of players, teams, board games, venues,
        tournaments, and matches &mdash; because apparently a "league" doesn't run itself. If you
        create an account, we store your name and email. If you lose a match badly enough, we
        <em>may</em> also store a mental note, but that data lives in the application's log files
        (see the Admin Logs page), not in your file.
    </p>

    <h4>2. What we don't collect</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Your browsing history on other sites (we're a board game tracker, not the FBI)</li>
        <li>Your actual dice-rolling technique, however questionable</li>
        <li>Any data via carrier pigeon, fax machine, or interpretive dance</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>3. Cookies</h4>
    <p>
        This site uses cookies for authentication, the same way board games use small plastic
        pieces: essential to the experience, easy to lose, and mildly stressful if a child gets
        near them. We do not use cookies to track you across the web, mostly because we forgot how.
    </p>

    <h4>4. Third-party services</h4>
    <p>
        We use Google for sign-in and Gemini for the AI assistant. Google knows what Google knows.
        Gemini occasionally forgets which model version it's allowed to be, which is between Gemini
        and its maker, not us.
    </p>

    <h4>5. Data retention</h4>
    <p>
        We keep your data for as long as the database is up, which, statistically speaking, is most
        of the time. Match results are kept indefinitely, because losing a tournament is a burden
        best carried forever.
    </p>

    <h4>6. Your rights</h4>
    <p>
        You have the right to access, correct, or delete your data, subject to whether an Admin is
        awake and logged in. You also have the right to remain silent about that time you tried to
        claim a house rule mid-tournament; anything you say can and will be used to settle the
        argument.
    </p>

    <h4>7. Security</h4>
    <p>
        We take reasonable measures to protect your data, including passwords, role-based access,
        and the sincere hope that nobody tries anything clever. No security measure is perfect,
        much like no board game has ever survived contact with a 6-year-old and a stack of
        Jenga blocks.
    </p>

    <h4>8. Changes to this policy</h4>
    <p>
        We may update this policy from time to time, typically right before someone important reads
        it.
    </p>

    <h4>9. Contact us</h4>
    <p>
        Questions about this policy can be directed to the League Admin, who will respond with the
        enthusiasm of someone asked to read the rulebook for Twilight Imperium out loud.
    </p>
</div>
